                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support><p>Almost square block of brown/grey stone. Top and bottom are certainly complete edges, the left and right edges, although abraded and are not perpendicular to the other edges, and probably original as well. Modern black paint on face, modern red paint on sides. Rear is relatively flat. Front face is deliberately pock-marked (Bivona (1994) suggests that this is due to the removal of a previous inscription, traces of which might be visible above the A and T in line 3).</p>
                                    <material ana="#material.stone.limestone" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/66.html">limestone</material>
                                    <objectType ana="#object.plaque" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/259.html">plaque</objectType>
                                  <dimensions>
                                        <height unit="cm">23.5</height>
                                        <width unit="cm">31.5</width>
                                        <depth unit="cm">9</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition/>
		    </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout><p>Three lines of Latin text. Lines 1-2 are centred on the stone, line 3 is at the extreme left of the stone. Use of large 'T' shaped interpuncts.</p>
                                    <rs ana="#execution.chiselled" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1">chiselled</rs>
                                	<damage/>
			</layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote><p>Letters are deeply incised. Letters in lines 1-2 are relatively straight, equally spaced and keep to the line, whereas line 3 is a little more varied in all of these features. Large serifs are used, particularly in the tail of the 'R' in line 1, and that of the 'L' in line 2.</p>
                                <locus from="line1" to="line1">Line 1</locus>
                                <dimensions type="letterHeight">
                                    <height unit="mm">48-55</height>
                                </dimensions>
                                <locus from="line2" to="line2">Line 2</locus>
                                <dimensions type="letterHeight">
